    "summary": "Strongest objection to \"character\": ambiguity without modifier",
    "content": "**Strongest objection:** \"Character\" without a modifier is ambiguous in exactly the wrong places. \"The character of a person\" can mean personality, moral standing, or a fictional role. \"All things have their character\" is vague enough that the reader must guess what is meant. The modifier (\"defining\" or \"constitutive\") is what forces the reader into the author's intended sense -- without it, the English word underdetermines the concept on every occurrence.\n\nThat said, if the 性 collision is off the table, then \"character\" is less dangerous than I initially thought. My concern is not that it is *wrong* but that it is *empty* -- it lets the reader fill in whatever meaning they bring, rather than guiding them toward the author's specific structural sense.\n"
